But the ark is the depository of the laws, for in that are placed the holy oracles of God, which were given to Moses;
ON THE LIFE OF MOSES. 95
and the covering of the ark, which is called the mercy-seat, is a foundation for two winged creatures to rest upon, which are called, in the native language if the Hebrews, cherubim, but as the Greeks would translate the word, vast knowledge and science. Now some persons say, that these cherubim are the symbols of the two hemispheres, placcd opposite to and fronting one another, the one beneath the earth and the other above the earth, for the whole heaven is endowed with wings.

Now the beginning of his divine inspiration, which was als» the commencement of prosperity to his nation, arose when he was sent out of Egypt to dwell as a settler in the cities of Syr.a, with many thousands of his countrymen; for both men and women, having accomplished together a long and desolate journey through the wilderness, destitute of any beaten road, at last arrived at the sea which is called the Red Se. Then, as was natural, they were in great perplexity, neither being able to cross over by reason of their want of vessels, nor think ng it safe to return back by the way by which they had come. And while they were all in this fate of mind, a still greater evil was impending over them;
ON THE LIFE OF MOSES. 127
for the king of the Egrpt ans, having collected a power which was far from contemptible, a vast army of cavalry and infantry, sallied forth in pursuit of them, and made haste to overtake them, that he might avenge himself on them for the departure which he had been compelled by undeniable communications from God to permit them to take.

And after he has forbidden stealing he proceeds in regular order to prohibit bearing false witness, knowing that those who bear false witness are liable to many great accusations, and in short to every kind of terrible charge ;
ON THE TEN COMMANDMENTS. 167
for in the first place they are corrupting that holy thing, truth, than which there is no more sacred possession among men, which like the sun sheds a light upon ali things, so that not one of them may be kept in darkness; and in the second place, in addition to speaking falsely, they also as it were envelop facts in night and dense darkness, and they co-operate with those who offend, and they join in attacking those who are injured by others, affirming that they positively know and have completely comprehended what they in reality have not seen nor heard, and of which they know nothing.

Then, O you most worthless of all men! I would say to them, have you not first learnt what you are now teaching ? or do you know how to invite other people to compassion even by the most inhuman actions, and yet have you eradicated all merciful and humane feelings from your own souls? And do you act in this way in spite of not being in want of good advisers, and especially of our laws, which have released even the earth from its yearly burdens, giving it a relaxation and a respite? and it, although it seems to be inanimate, is nevertheless fully prepared to make a requital and to recompence favours, hastening to pay back any gift which it has received ;
278 PHILO JUDAZUS,
for as it receives an exemption every seventh year, and is not’ forced to exert itself that year, but is set wholly free for the whole circle of the year,.in the subsequent year produces double, or sometimes, many times, larger crops than usual from its great productiveness.

For, indeed, his servants at all times steadfastly observed
him, as subjects observe a ruler, looking with admiration at
the universal greatness of his nature and disposition, which
was more perfect than is customary to meet with in a man;
for he did not use the same conversation as ordinary men, but,
like one inspired, spoke in general in more dignified language.
